## Performance Optimization

### State Management Optimization

```hcl
# BAD: Large monolithic state (slow operations)
# All resources in one state file

# GOOD: Separate states by change frequency
# networking/ (rarely changes)
# compute/ (moderate changes)
# applications/ (frequent changes)
```

### Data Source Optimization

```hcl
# BAD: Repeated data source calls
resource "aws_instance" "web1" {
  ami = data.aws_ami.ubuntu.id
}
resource "aws_instance" "web2" {
  ami = data.aws_ami.ubuntu.id  # Same data source called again
}

# GOOD: Cache data source result
locals {
  ami_id = data.aws_ami.ubuntu.id
}

resource "aws_instance" "web1" {
  ami = local.ami_id
}
resource "aws_instance" "web2" {
  ami = local.ami_id
}
```

### Parallelization

```bash
# BAD: Sequential operations
terraform apply -target=module.vpc
terraform apply -target=module.compute
terraform apply -target=module.app

# GOOD: Parallel operations (Terraform handles automatically)
terraform apply  # All independent resources run in parallel
```

### Plan Optimization

```bash
# Save plan for consistency
terraform plan -out=tfplan

# Review plan
terraform show tfplan

# Apply saved plan (faster, consistent)
terraform apply tfplan

# Plan specific resources
terraform plan -target=module.vpc
```

## Troubleshooting Guide

### Debug Logging
```bash
# Enable debug logging
export TF_LOG=DEBUG
export TF_LOG_PATH=terraform-debug.log
terraform apply

# Log levels: TRACE, DEBUG, INFO, WARN, ERROR
export TF_LOG=TRACE  # Most verbose

# Filter by module
export TF_LOG=DEBUG
export TF_LOG_PATH=terraform-debug.log
terraform apply -target=module.vpc
```

### Common Error Patterns

**Provider Version Conflicts:**

```bash
# Error: Provider version constraint conflict
# Solution: Update provider versions
terraform init -upgrade

# Or pin specific version
terraform {
  required_providers {
    aws = {
      source  = "hashicorp/aws"
      version = "~> 6.0"
    }
  }
}
```

**State Lock Issues:**

```bash
# Error: Error acquiring the state lock
# Solution: Check for stuck locks
aws dynamodb scan --table-name terraform-locks

# Force unlock (use with caution)
terraform force-unlock <LOCK_ID>

# Check lock details
terraform force-unlock -force <LOCK_ID>
```

**Resource Already Exists:**

```bash
# Error: resource already exists
# Solution: Import existing resource
terraform import aws_vpc.this vpc-0abc1234

# Or use import blocks (Terraform 1.5+)
import {
  to = aws_vpc.this
  id = "vpc-0abc1234"
}
```

**Module Source Issues:**

```bash
# Error: Failed to download module
# Solution: Check module source
terraform get -update

# Verify module path
terraform providers
```

### State Issues

#### Locked State
```bash
# View lock info
terraform force-unlock <LOCK_ID>

# If DynamoDB locking, check DynamoDB table for lock record
aws dynamodb scan --table-name terraform-locks
```

#### Corrupted State
```bash
# Pull state locally
terraform state pull > backup.tfstate

# Restore from backup
terraform state push backup.tfstate

# Remove corrupted resource from state
terraform state rm aws_instance.broken

# Re-import resource
terraform import aws_instance.broken i-0abc1234def56789
```

#### Drift Detection
```bash
# Refresh state from real infrastructure
terraform apply -refresh-only

# Show what changed
terraform plan -refresh-only
```

### Plan/Apply Failures

#### Dependency Cycle
```
Error: Cycle: aws_security_group.web, aws_security_group.app
```

**Solution**: Break circular reference with separate resources or `depends_on`

```hcl
# Use separate security group rules instead of inline rules
resource "aws_security_group_rule" "web_to_app" {
  type                     = "ingress"
  from_port                = 443
  to_port                  = 443
  protocol                 = "tcp"
  source_security_group_id = aws_security_group.web.id
  security_group_id        = aws_security_group.app.id
}
```

#### Resource Already Exists
```
Error: resource already exists
```

**Solution**: Import existing resource or rename in state

```bash
# Import existing resource
terraform import aws_vpc.this vpc-0abc1234

# Or rename Terraform resource
terraform state mv aws_vpc.old aws_vpc.new
```

